00:02:16.210 --> 00:02:18.100
Yeah, we're all about new plays.

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:21.650
And "Marie and Rosetta"
is a great new play.

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:23.480
It's written by George Brant.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:27.310
I was sent the play last year
from a producer friend of mine,

00:02:27.310 --> 00:02:29.220
and I knew about George's work.

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:30.940
George wrote a play
called "Grounded,"

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:33.320
that was at the Public
Theater last season with Anne

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.890
Hathaway about drone bombing.

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:37.580
And he's a wonderful writer.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:41.160
And so I wasn't quite sure what
to expect when I got this play.

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:44.480
And I read it, and I thought
this is kind of extraordinary.

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:47.690
Here is this amazing woman,
Sister Rosetta Tharpe,

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:50.250
who has been dubbed the
godmother of rock and roll,

00:02:50.250 --> 00:02:52.460
and I had never heard of her.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:55.100
And I consider myself
to be a rock and roll

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:58.570
fan and a fan of blues music
and a fan of gospel music.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:01.100
And so then I immediately--
thanks to you guys, I

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:02.470
went to YouTube.

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:06.210
And I started researching more
about Sister Rosetta Tharpe,

00:03:06.210 --> 00:03:10.450
and, lo and behold, there were
all these incredible songs.

00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:12.260
And here was this
amazing woman who

00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:15.320
started in gospel in
the 1930s and then

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:18.650
kind of moved into more popular
music in the 40s and 50s.

00:03:18.650 --> 00:03:21.300
And not only was she
a great songwriter

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:25.490
and a great vocalist, but as
you'll see, if you YouTube her,

00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:29.070
or if you come and see the show,
she was an amazing guitarist.

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:33.780
And so in the late 30s,
here was this woman who

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:37.140
took out an electric guitar and
played it like nobody really

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:40.720
played it before and--
what we found out later--

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:45.520
ended up influencing people like
Jimi Hendrix and Chuck Berry.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:47.640
I was amazed because I'd
been a huge Chuck Berry

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:51.600
fan and a lot of the riffs that
Chuck Berry plays are directly

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:53.790
from Sister Rosetta.

00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:57.750
So here was this play that
was not only celebrating

00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:00.610
this woman, who
sadly is not known,

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:03.590
but it was also talking
about the history

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:05.450
of 20th-century music.

00:04:05.450 --> 00:04:08.020
And it was
celebrating two women,

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:11.150
because it concentrates on the
meeting between Sister Rosetta

00:04:11.150 --> 00:04:13.960
and another phenomenal
singer called Marie Knight.

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:17.399
And they got together
and sort of performed

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:20.410
as a duo in the late 40s.

00:04:20.410 --> 00:04:22.570
And so the play
concentrates on that.

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:25.600
And what George was able to
do is kind of compress a lot

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:28.480
of factual information
about their relationship

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:32.200
and then show us some of
the songs that Rosetta wrote

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.800
and talk a little bit
about Marie Knight as well.

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:38.300
So for us it was a
great opportunity,

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:40.010
because we're all
about telling stories

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:42.310
that we think are
important to be told,

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:44.250
and we're about
celebrating great writing

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:46.320
and the truth of great writing.

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:49.060
This was an amazing
story to tell.

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:53.710
And just the fact that--
well, I should also say we

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:57.770
feel blessed to have these
incredible performers.

00:04:57.770 --> 00:05:00.880
The fact that these
women were not known

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:04.220
and then for all of us to come
together and celebrate them

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:06.470
was a big deal for us.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:11.410
